[ProMED-mail thanks Mahmoud Orabi for submitting this report.

This is yet another example of movement of _Aedes aegypti_ to a new location. The possible mechanism of transport in this case is not mentioned. This is the 2nd report of the appearance of _A. aegypti_ in the Canary Islands. The 1st was in 2017. The entomological surveillance in the Islands has been very effective in detecting the presence of _A. aegypti_ very early on and eliminating them. The risk of new introductions of this mosquito is ongoing. One hopes that surveillance and response will continue to be successful in preventing the establishment of this mosquito or others in the Canary Islands. - Mod.TY]
